title: Folgertech FT-5 R1 Single Motor Z axis

description.text:
Just like many FT-5 owners, I have had the same old problem with the Z motors getting out of sync. I was going to do the sync belt mod that many have come up with. But, decided to go a different route.

THIS is a no frills, eyeball type mod. No plans, measurement or anything of the like. Since Folgertech is now selling the R2 model, they have made available parts for the the new model, including the long belt and idler pulleys for the Z axis.

Belt here:

https://folgertech.com/collections/beltandpulleys/products/987-gt2-6mm-belt-loop

Idlers here (need 2):

https://folgertech.com/products/idler-pulley-for-gt2-belt

Also need, 2 - M5 x 30 mm all thread bolts, (don't remember the thread pitch), 4 - nylon lock nuts, 8 - 5 mm flat washers, 5 mm drill bit, and a 5 mm hole center punch.

1> Remove the lead screws for the Z axis.
2> Place the belt around the screws and reinstall.
3> Remove the motor you are not going to use, I simply unplugged mine and left the
harness.
4> Very IMPORTANT!! Guesstimate the location of the idlers. Also, do not drill into your
motor or wiring, probably best to drill with the printer on it side so you can see
everything.
5> Install bolt, washer under head, then wash under lock nut, lock in place, then washer on
top of nut, place idler, another washer, then another lock nut, tighten till snug, back off
till the pulley spins free.
6> Level up the bed, lock everything down, and go printing.

It took me about an hour goofing off, re-leveled my bed, and went right to printing, so all good! Remember, your mileage my vary.

DISCLAIMER:
I am not responsible if you drill into your motor or your finger.

I hope this helps someone.

p.s. The cover is for a Hummingbird Fish Finder, PiranhaMax 4.

description.text:
Edit: Jan/26/2018 - updated the fan shrouds with a new, uniform design

We took an existing hotend mount on Thingiverse and modified it for improved fit and ease of use. This hotend mount will correctly mount a titan extruder, while the original version remixed from does not (the stepper mounting plate was too thick for proper tightening of the titan mounting screws) We also modified it for ease of mounting, by putting in a relief for the hotend carriage as it has a nut and bolt that can interfere with the original design. This version also has a single mounting screw as it gets locked into position with the 2 extruded screw holes originally used for the stock hotend. This allows the entire assembly to be removed without any disassembly of any component. We also added an additional cable mount which really stiffens your wire harness up so that it isn't flopping around and does not require additional support.

the back of the this mount has 4 nut traps for using M3 screws to mount the fans. they are slightly undersized as they need to be heated with a soldering iron or lighter and then pushed into place so they don't come out.

The attached photo shows the mounting hole used with a 12mm M3 screw and a lock washer. Lock washer is critically important as the screw can come loose otherwise

description.text:
Edit: Jan/26/2018 - updated the fan shrouds with a new, uniform design

We took an existing hotend mount on Thingiverse and modified it for improved fit and ease of use. This hotend mount will correctly mount a titan extruder, while the original version remixed from does not (the stepper mounting plate was too thick for proper tightening of the titan mounting screws) We also modified it for ease of mounting, by putting in a relief for the hotend carriage as it has a nut and bolt that can interfere with the original design. This version also has a single mounting screw as it gets locked into position with the 2 extruded screw holes originally used for the stock hotend. This allows the entire assembly to be removed without any disassembly of any component. We also added an additional cable mount which really stiffens your wire harness up so that it isn't flopping around and does not require additional support.

the back of the this mount has 4 nut traps for using M3 screws to mount the fans. they are slightly undersized as they need to be heated with a soldering iron or lighter and then pushed into place so they don't come out.

The attached photo shows the mounting hole used with a 12mm M3 screw and a lock washer. Lock washer is critically important as the screw can come loose otherwise

title: Blinking Christmas Tree - Modified Battery Base

description.text:
The Blinking Christmas tree is a great design that turned out awesome! While I was preparing to print the model, I found a nice set of pre-wired, battery-powered (3 x AA) Christmas led lights for US$4 which allowed me to sidestep the electrical work entirely--outside of some very minor soldering (had to remove 5 of the bulbs from their holders so that they would fit in the shallower holes of the tree where some were near a structural edge which meant the bulb base was too broad to fit snugly).

Obviously, since I decided to use battery-powered lights, I needed to modify the base to make the battery pack fit. Overall, I feel my adjustments worked very well, though adding the battery pack did add a substantial amount of mass to the base versus what Alzibiff had with their base (which was very well-done in its own right), but it isn't a show stopper by any means.

Things to consider:

  • The battery slot in the base is 90mm x 54mm x 21mm and fits my 3 x AA battery pack with switch well, though as a warning the tolerances are on the tighter side, so if your machine cuts close, you may want to go right of the line and scale up a percent or two (or more).
  • I also considered adding a shallow channel in the battery slot to accommodate the battery wires feeding into the tree, if this is something someone would like, just let me know and I can add it, otherwise opening it in a any CAD program and adding in a negative space channel shouldn't take more than a few minutes.
  • Also, since the slot is effectively a rectangular prism less one side, there is the potential for failure on the top of the battery pack slot; I was able to print without supports, but I cannot say how well this will work for other machines.

Pro tip: we also used some superglue to hold the lights in place in the tree - no sense waiting for one to pop into the tree during transit to Grandma's house!

title: LED Christmas Tree Ornament - Removable Battery

description.text:
This easy to assemble ornament will light your decor and warm your hearts!

I love the tree design in the original posting, but I wanted a way to easily replace the battery and keep the tree light close to the ornament for maximum lighting effect - thus the hybrid design was inspired.

By adapting the original base slightly (adding an extending channel for a more reliable battery connection and ensuring the sizing would match), I created a simple and stylish tree ornament that my wife made me print 60 of for all her friends and family.

With this design, you get optimal functionality through easy battery replacement and structural integrity, with the sleek and festive design of a well-lit tree (pick a fun changing color LED for added pizzazz!).

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Resolution:

.15

.2

Notes:

I printed the base with Inland Natural PLA 1.75mm Filament using Prusa Factory Default Optimal PLA settings in Slic3r.

Assemble wiring for the LED in the base (follow directions in the original tree base post - they are great and easy to follow). We added the small channel in the battery port to keep the circuit more reliably snug - so make sure the short leg of the battery runs over the channel and is secured tightly. You will likely have excess wiring when you are done so be ready to trim the extra length.

Pro Top: TEST the assembly by sliding the battery into the base - in and out a few times to confirm your base is solid and nothing is loose/missing the connection.

Align the tree posts (legs) with their corresponding channels (thinner leg to thin channel, thicker leg to larger channel). Before assembling the tree onto the base, we placed a few drops of liquid superglue inside each base channel and on the inner sidewalls to hold it securely. When you insert the legs into the base and push down, the LED light should easily slide into the hole meant for it on the bottom portion of the tree (you shouldntt have to bend or press hard for it to find its way).

Once the tree is securely in place, add a few more drops of superglue to the outside edges of each tree leg connection point and let dry.

We assembled 60 of these for family and it was very easy once I got the design right.

The Comp XL measure 121mm diagonally and is an easy to print micro quadcopter frame which has been enlarged from the original version to allow 3" props.

We have produced three different versions:

The Basher – This version of our original design has extended arms, but is in all other ways identical to its smaller cousin, maintaining the motor mount spacing for 11XX size motors.

The Cruiser – This version has thinner arms than the larger "Basher" version, which will of course result in reduced durability. It also retains the same motor mount spacing for 11XX size motors.

Remember that the outside holes will line up with a full size flight controller mounting pattern, so you can use one of the many already available camera mounts, or use one of the flight controller stack plates as the base of your own design.
  • The models should be printed logo side down for best results, and it is recommended that you take the time to orient your infill to align with the arms to increase overall strength.
  • Experiment with materials, settings, and remember to have fun!

description.text:
I was looking at ways to better manage my wiring for a new printer build and thought "Hey, some terminal blocks would be darn handy". I found a severe lack of decent ones on here so I decided to throw a snazzy one together right quick.

This handy dandy little terminal block comes in two pieces and 8 pre-made sizes. It's designed to work with standard m3 bolts and nuts. all that is required to assemble is a soldering iron and possibly a knife for cleaning up the edges.

Assembly instructions:

Print off both the top and bottom sections
.
Make sure the top can nest into the channels of the bottom.If your printer is over extruding or a little messy there could be a bit of shmoo to clean up with a knife.

Once it is nesting just fine use a soldering iron to press the m3 nuts into the premade slots of the bottom. Attach the top to the bottom and then use the end holes to screw it into whatever you like ( note, I'm not responsible for you screwing it into inappropriate things, or wiring something stupid heavy using these and burning your house/trailer/cat down)

There are options from 1 terminal up to 8 premade. There is also a sketchup file with each version and the building blocks to make your own. I figured 8 was a good ending point as it fit nicely on my current print bed.

title: Santa’s Sleigh Ride - Christmas Dice Game

description.text:
Every year we do some variant of White Elephant for a Christmas Eve gathering of a bunch of family. It's usually more involved than your typical White Elephant, having a game like bingo or LCR or something to kick it off, then having multiple gifts and a "pot" of small gifts, and every year the rules and number of gifts is different.

For this year's game my wife and I made a new game, and I made a custom D12 die for the occasion that goes along with the rules.

Synopsis
Everyone brings 2 gifts - totaling no more than $10 combined (or your call for price limit on your game). Everyone starts with 1 gift in front of them and 1 in the pot (aka "the sleigh").
Take turns going around the table, rolling the big Christmas D12 and doing what the die says. There'll be a lot of swapping gifts, stealing gifts, passing gifts, and opening gifts. Even the occasional battle. When all the gifts in front of everyone (not in the sleigh) are open, that part of the game is over. Then you play LCR to see who wins the sleigh, winner takes all for it.

Directions
All wrapped gifts (2 per player) are put into ‘Santa’s sleigh’ in the center of the table.  Each Silly Santa chooses one wrapped gift and places it in front of them.  Each Santa then takes turns rolling the Christmas die and follows the instructions to trade, steal, pass or unwrap their gift.  Santa may encounter blizzards, naughty elves, re-gifting and snowball fights along the way! The game ends when all gifts OUT OF THE SLEIGH are unwrapped. Play starts with the youngest player and moves to the next player on the left.  Note that many of the presents will be left in the sleigh at the end of the game. 

The idea is to play LCR with Christmas themed chips for a winner takes all battle for the remaining presents in the sleigh.

GENERAL RULES:

  • All gifts passed, traded, or stolen are done so wrapped or unwrapped at any time in the game.

  • Each player will always have a minimum of 1 gift and maximum of 2 gifts at any time in the game.
  • Gifts are only unwrapped when the ‘OPEN’ options (see below) are rolled.

CHRISTMAS DIE INSTRUCTIONS

  1. BLIZZARD LEFT – all players pass 1 gift to the player on their left.
  2. BLIZZARD RIGHT – all players pass 1 gift to the player on their right.
  3. REGIFT LEFT – trade 1 gift with the player on your left.
  4. REGIFT RIGHT – trade 1 gift with the player on your right.
  5. REGIFT ANYONE – trade 1 gift with 1 other player of choice. If either player has 2 gifts, it is the choice of the roller on which gifts to trade.
  6. OPEN GIFT – unwrap ONE gift in your possession. If player does not have a gift to unwrap, roll again. This side appears twice on the die, intentionally, to speed up the game a bit.
  7. OPEN THEIR GIFT - player chooses to unwrap 1 gift of ANOTHER player. No gifts are traded or stolen.
  8. NAUGHTY ELF – take 1 gift from the sleigh (limited to half the sleigh. Once half the sleigh has already been stolen, there are no more to steal and player rolls again). DO NOT UNWRAP. If a player already has 2 gifts in their possession, they can choose to:
    a. pass a gift to a player with only 1 gift and take a gift from the sleigh or
    b. roll again.
  9. SNEAKY ELF – trade 1 gift with a gift in the sleigh.
  10. NICE ELF – Only applies when the player has 2 gifts. If player does not have 2 gifts, roll again. If the player has 2 gifts, choose one gift to return to the sleigh. A wrapped gift must be returned before an unwrapped gift.
  11. SNOWBALL FIGHT – player chooses 1 other player to battle. Both players roll the 6 sided die 1 time. The player with the higher number WINS the battle. The WINNER does one of the following:
    a. Do nothing and keep 1 or both gifts in their possession.
    b. Trade 1 or both gifts with the loser.
    c. Take 1 of the loser’s gifts if the loser has 2 gifts.
    Reminder: Each player will always have a minimum of 1 gift and maximum of 2 gifts at any time.

DICE FONT NOTES
The fonts I used were all either stock windows fonts (the regift ones) or were found on the web and marked free for personal use. This die should not be sold commercially, or you will be violating the license of the owners of those fonts. I don't have links to the makers of the fonts, since I'm not interested in selling this (unless you ask me nice ;)

Painting
As you can see, I had fun painting this die. I used acrylic paints and a variety of cheap small brushes with as pointy of an edge as I can get. And to get in all the tight spots, I typically paint with a toothpick (yeah, really). I don't worry about messing it up, after I'm done with the colors there's always splotches and I go back with white to clean it up and crisp up the lines and it really makes it look almost pro.

description.text:
Despite all the filament clips out there, none seemed to work well for me - either they pop off the spool rim, are hard to thread the filament through, or allow the filament to slide out.

This is clip will tightly and independently grip two strands of filament. If toleranced and printed properly, the filament will "click" into place and not slip, even for glossy filament.

This prints well in PLA and uses only a few cm of filament per clip.

The customizer should allow for any size filament, but I have not tested anything other 1.75mm.

UPDATE 12/16/17: Changed OpenSCAD model to avoid "coincident faces" issues in preview and any possible non-manifold objects. Regenerated STL files, but no functional change.

Printer:

Craftbot2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

No

Notes:

PLA works great, nice and stiff. PETG might be OK too, I did not try yet. Since object is so small, print 6 or more up at once to give the layers time to set.

Make sure the Z "seam" is not inside of the clip face, which is the default in Cura and probably other slicers. If it is, it will cause interference and prevent the filament from snapping in fully..

In Cura 3, I recommend setting "Seam Corner Preference" to "Expose Seam" to avoid this.

I also use "Horizontal Offset" set to -0.05mm in Cura as this renders truer diameters on holes for me. If you don't then add "-0.05" to the offset for a more negative value in the customizer.

The above will get you started, but you may need to tweak for your printer and slicer.

Make sure throat of clips is free from stray filament threads (boogers).

Clips should snap firmly and audibly onto filament, and not slide easily.

If filament slides out, make "offset" value more negative in 0.05 increments until snug. If clip is too hard to install, make "offset" more positive in 0.05 increments.
Lots of trial and error.

title: Parametric motorcycle/bicycle handlebar watch mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is a mount designed to replace the band from any standard watch, to mount to any handlebar or other round tube. The included STL file is designed to mount a Casio F-91W to a standard 7/8" (22.25mm) motorcycle handlebar with a #6-32 x 1 in. machine screw and nut. (use a locking nut for best results)

It is designed to minimize print time, and work without hinges. I have tested with PETG and PLA and it retains enough flexibility to go over the handlebar without breaking.

The Fusion 360 file that is included should allow you to modify the mount to fit many different watches, handlebars, and bolts (within reason). The following are the parameters that you may want to change:

  • bardiameter - default 22.25mm - the diameter of the hole for the handlebar
  • pindiameter - default 1mm - the diameter of the pin that goes through the watch band
  • strapdiameter - default 3.5mm - the total thickness of the strap where it goes around the pin and attaches to the watch
  • strapwidth - default 18mm - the size of the watch band
  • pincenterdistance - default 35mm - the distance between both pins on the watch, measured to the center of the pin opening
  • casebacktopincenter - default 2.25mm - the distance between the centerline of the pin and the back of the case, in other words, the distance that the pins need to come up from the back of the case. Err on the side of too much, rather than too little.
  • screwhole - default 4mm - the diameter of the hole for the fastener. Round up with your measurements so that it doesn't fit too tight.
  • headrecessdiameter - default 7mm - the diameter of the countersink. Again, round this up a little bit because a snug fit is not desirable.
  • nutdiameter - default 8mm - the size of the nut measured from flat-to-flat. You may or may not want to round this up depending on if you'd like the nut to be retained and your particular printer.
  • nutrecessdepth - default 3mm - a recessed pocket for the nut so that you don't need to use a wrench on the back side.

But none that did enough.

So I dug into the SCAD code and found the alignment of the belt centre was offset to the bearing rail centre. The cause of many peoples pain. According to the code, it was offset by 2mm. A small amount, but enough to cause a grinding issue on the idler belt wheel.

Fix the code and here is the model. Now I have perfectly smooth motion.

Josef Prusa and his team have done an amazing job and all hats off to them.

description.text:
HS5 locking mechanism for retrofitting aftermarket LED bulbs into the stock Honda PCX headlight. One only fits LED bulbs with an outside diameter of 18 mm. It uses the headlight bulb gasket from the halogen bulbs that were on the scoot already. I also designed a plug adapter for the wiring harness plug, so that no wires need to be cut on the scoot. The plug requires some cheap Chinese made spade connectors and some crazy glue to hold them in place. The rear headlight cover might need some re scaling to fit snugly and stay in place.

I'm currently working on a better LED light that mimics the stock halogen bulb better, although its a two color bulb. I got the LED kit on eBay, its a 9006 LED retrofit kit.

title: Traxxas 5247 to Carbon Tube Coupler With Compression Lock

description.text:
This coupler was created to serve a specific purpose: to connect the Traxxas 5347 ball joints to 1/2" carbon fiber tubes for use on the large Delta style 3d printer I'm creating, based on parts and designs for the Mini Kossel.   
I'm using 24" long and 0.5" outer diameter carbon fiber tubes for the effector arms. So there is a bit of a "gap" between the Traxxas joint shafts, which measures around ~7mm in its outer diameter.  
The inner diameter of the Traxxas shaft takes an M4 threaded bolt.   
If you are building a large delta printer and are using Traxxas 4257 joints and want to use a large diameter shaft, this might be of help.   
Work in progress, so only uploading the STL at this point.  
I mainly designed this because I didn't like using glue and wanted something I can adjust/maintain. Hence this design.   
Update:   
Added a another STL, which does not have the little balls, for those who want to do their own support material. Also, after printing it, the balls really don't want to be removed. :)  Though they will flex a bit to allow capture of the carbon fiber tube/rod.  
Note:  
The ridges in the photographs are due to ribbing on my printer(cheap threaded rod). A printer without the issues of my printer will print smooth walls.

To connect this component:
  • Print the part. I suggest 50% infill or 100% infill.
  • Snap/break off the little ball supports. Clean any loose threads of plastic/etc.
  • Insert the Traxxas shaft into the cone side of the sleeve.
  • Take an M4 bolt, 5-8mm M4 should be fine. I would add a washer to distribute the pressure, but screw it in from the larger opening side of the coupler through the hole and into the Traxxas shaft. This secures the Traxxas ball joint to the coupler.
  • Slide the 1/2" carbon fiber tube into the wide end of the coupler.
  • Take an M3 bolt and M3 nut and slowly tighten the compression tabs to secure the carbon fiber tube. If you have a very thin sheet of silicone or other grippy/non-abrasive material as a sleeve between the compression ring and the carbon fiber tube, that would help.
    ** If you are concerned about the carbon fiber tube cracking under pressure, you can fit in a carbon fiber rod into the larger tube, making sure the clearance is tight. My carbon fiber tubes were 0.4" inner diameter, so I would need to get a 0.396" outer diameter rod/tube. YMMV.
  • Test the strength of the connection by pulling/pushing. There should be no give.
  • Rinse and repeat with the remaining effector arms and make sure they are all the same length. If all parts printed the same and all your rods are cut the same, this should not be a problem. However, if you do need to adjust, loosen the compression M3 and adjust until all rods match in length. A jig would help with this.
    • Hints:
  • A thin sheet of silicone between the coupler and the carbon tube/rod will work wonders for preventing slippage, if the compression of slippery PLA against slippery carbon fiber tubes doesn't prevent slippage. :)

description.text:
Calibration for hole size, as well as X, Y and Z for SLA printers

My guide sleeve wouldn't fit inside my first DLP print. (it did fit into an FDM print with a 101% scale) What I didn't know is that you need to offset your custom sleeve sizes in Blue Sky Plan. I needed a way to find the precise sleeve offset for my surgical guides. I could design and print several different guides, but I decided to design a "pseudo guide" with seven sample holes in it.

I've decided to share the Tinkercad file so you can edit it to the diameters specific to your needs. Simply click the green sleeve holes, and enter the desired diameter. Then click the text and edit each of those as necessary.

I am releasing this for free to the 3d dental community. My one request is that credit is attributed to me for any derivative designs. One scenario I can think of is someone modifying this for all the blueskybio implant sleeves.

To customize this in your web browser, I've provided the Tinkercad file at the bottom of the description. Don't know how to use Tinkercad? Here's a screencast showing how to change the dimensions of the sleeve holes. http://youtu.be/blqF-dIh0Dc?hd=1

What's new in version 2.0
1) condensed below 80mm long to fit on Moonray S bed in either direction
2) arc shaped body reduces slice area for more reliable SLA printing
3) now fits 7 test holes instead of 5
4) 20mm and 10mm calibration features removed to streamline the design. If you miss them, you can always print a separate calibration cube on the same batch.

What's new in version 1.2
1) totally new base. It's shorter in X and Z dimensions, so it should print a bit faster

What's new in version 1.13:
1) Esthetic tweaks

What's new in version 1.12:
1) shrank the base holes
2) cleaned up some duplicate polygons
3) got the 80mm mark to show
4) added the name of the implant for identification

What's new in version 1.1:
1) Added the 4mm platform to get above the squish, and then added "skis" to raft it up. Thanks to Barry Voltz for suggesting these features.
2) Added 80mm X calibration (The arch and the 3mm stilt should both be 80mm long) Sorry, but Tinkercad was being fussy and wouldn't let me carve the 80mm into the base.
3) Added 20mm Y calibration feature to the side
4) Added 10mm Z calibration feature to the side. You can also caliper the rings themselves--they are 5mm thick by default.
5) Reduced base holes and increased tire widths to reduce chance of getting "islands" when drill diameter is shrunk too much.
6) Sample size is 5.3mm, which corresponds to the BlueSkyBio Max NP tubes for 4.3mm implants. Just a subtle shoutout to my friends at BlueSkyBio Academy.

I attached the blower fan to the right side of the original shroud using a M3x20 screw in the top fan mounting hole. Since the screw was loose in the fan, I added 2 layers of heat shrink to the first 15mm to make a simple shoulder bolt, then it fit through the fan, the shroud, and into the X carriage mounting hole without wobble.

This lamp is inspirited by the Lotus flower.
It consists out of 12 separate leaves that can move because each has its own SG90 servo.
These servos are controlled by an Arduino Uno. My intention was to control the servo’s by a light sensitive resistor (and it worked well), but for assembly I used a potentiometer. I also added a simple Arduino sketch for making assembly easier. It works with one potentiometer that controls al the leaves. If you don’t know how to install the servos and the potentiometer (light sensor) please consult the Arduino website: https://www.arduino.cc/en/Tutorial/Knob
In this sketch I divided them in 6 pairs. See picture.

The Leaves and LED holder are printed in “spiral vase mode”. One pair of leaves is printed as a vase. After printing this “leave vase” you have to cut them out with scissors. Most of the leaves I printed with a 0.4 mm nozzle and cutting them went very well. But the orange big ones I printed with a 0.5mm nozzle and that was much harder to cut. I recommend using only one or two layers on the base (bottom). That makes cutting these leaves out easier to. Then I glued the leaves to the holders.
The LED holder is also printed in “spiral vase mode” and for installing the LEDs I made little holes at the top for the wires that go to the LEDs. At the bottom (the side that goes into the hole) I cut out 2 slots. This way it’s possible to put the led holder in the hole and the servo wires can still pass. See picture

The LEDs themselves are 1w and have to be glued on a heat sink. I made these heat sinks of little pieces of aluminum (in flower style). If you don’t know how to drive these LED’s you can consult another model: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2662544

The Base is printed “the normal way” and needs support material.
Mounting the arms of the leaves to the servo the screws that come with the servos can be used. In my case I didn’t even use a screw. I included “servo test fit peace” so you can test fit the mounting hole of the “leave arms/holders”.
Then you need 4 M3x10 bolts and 4 nuts. The Servos are installed without screws and fit like Legos.
For the bottom lid you need small wood screws (or the ones that come with the sg90 servos).

Printed in PET-G

This is my first model I have ever made in a 3d designing program.
Instructions: Place the rings over the main body, so that the grove taken out around the rim is closest to the handle of the cryptex. Then mark each flat space around the ring so that the key letter that you want to be used is above the notch that goes all the way through, and not the small notches.When you have assembled it you will want to glue the cap ring to the end sealing the rings of letters. Then you will want to glue the pegs inside the notches on the inner cryptex body (I would recomend super glue) Then you may insert a note into the inside and close it up. Notes:The pegs should go in, so that the curved sides are sideways, and allign themselves wth the curvature of the rings. This will most likely require some filing down to get everything to fit right (I don\'t know how accurate your 3d printer is).
You might want to try to file down a little bit off the edges of the rings to allow you to put in a spacer in between each letter ring (Sorry I didn\'t include that) I have also included notches in the inside of the letter rings, to prevent lock picking....Thanks Marcus. I would reccomend you print the inner and outer body with the large end on bottom so you dont have to worry about the overhang. (this design has not been tested since I don\'t have a 3d printer) Please let me know if you print this out, I would really like to see it! license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I liked wstein’s Customizable Measuring Cup/Scoop, but, as i (still) have no filament fan, i have a problem with 45° overhangs. So i put the scoop upright again. Print this with falsework.

Elsewhere i complained about the use of a ton of units, and i still try to get everyone to use practical units. Americans should look up the millilitres per teaspoon &c. in this ist, and visit metric4us at their leisure after they printed their scoop.
As a reminder to everybody, millilitre and ml are just synonyms for cubic centimetre and cm³.

Printer:

GeeeTech i3 pro C

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200 µm

Infill:

15 %

Notes:

You need falsework for the handle. See above and below.

I just slightly tweaked this from wstein’s original. See the “remixed from” thing for details.

The size may be off a little bit more than the original. This is not a precision tool, just a rough measure.

There are more things to change than accessible in the customizer. Download the scad file, get OpenSCAD running on your PC and change them that way, if you want.

There is a little bit of history of my changes available at my github repo.

Take care when you use 3D printed parts with food.

  • PLA seems to be better suited for food use than ABS, so you should use that. Or maybe PETG
  • You should probably clean your nozzle once, to get rid of mineral oil and other residues.
  • When you use an oiler, use a suitable oil. Maybe a vegetable oil or something like Ballistol oil.

These two articles shed some more light on the issue:

  • 10 things you need to know about 3D printing & food safety
  • Food Safe Video

In the end, it is up to you. I can take no responsibility.

falsework: a temporary frame serving to support and brace a building under construction until it can stand alone.

In other word, those structures that you sometimes need when printing overhangs.My guess is that the first people that wrote a slicer just didn’t know that word, maybe even the large scale construction concept, and reinvented the wheel and named it the “circular transportation facilitation device”. Or “supports”. I try my best to use the correct word, falsework, when possible.

title: Find My Planets - Guessing Game (Battleship style)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is Find My Planets!

A guessing game inspired by the already classic Battleship pastime.


It's a 2-player game where you'll have to Discover all of your opponent's Planetary System. From its Star, to its 2 Gas Giants, its 3 Rocky Planets, and even its 5 Moons.

For this game, I've added a few "extras" to make it both more fun and lasting, as well as some learning basics on space exploration.

You will launch your Space Probes hoping to Detect or Find any of the Celestial Bodies. But do not forget about the importance of their location in space! Gas Giants are probably not going to orbit very close to its Star, and Moons will always have to orbit a Planet.

Here you have the complete Game Instructions with hopefully everything you'll need. Including Setup, Intended Gameplay & Rules, Pieces Needed, or My Printing Colors.


Fun and educational sort-of game for all ages that I hope you'll enjoy!

I recommend printing all Celestial Bodies in their "use position" with supports. Ie: their "legs" pointing downwards.

I printed my Divider with the lettering facing down to avoid imperfections in pin-holes. I used rafts which do not provide a perfect finish, but at least it secures well the prints.

I printed the Space Probes vertically "upside down". Ie: sat vertically but starting from the smaller stick area until reaching the square. Think as a the letter t upside down. Although I'm thinking that to avoid strings and excessive post-printing, maybe laying them horizontally with tiny supports should be the way to go.

For Deck and Launch Site you can just sit them down straight at their base.

description.header: Printing Times (0.4 Nozzle, 15% Infill, Supports & Rafts)
description.text:
Celestial Bodies take around 10-40mins, depending on their size.

Deck and Divider can take around 7-9hrs each.

Space Probes can take up to 2 hrs printing 100 pieces at a time

Color in Letters and Numbers

I used paint markers (POSCA type) because it's incredibly easy and painting isn't one of my virtues. For a more "pro-look", you can do a great paint/spray job and customize everything, but please share the result ;).


Space Probes don't fit tight in Divider holes

At first attempt you may have to snuggle them a bit, or simply sharpen the end-point with some flush cutters.


Divider doesn't fit tight in Deck

Just cut a tiny corner on one side of the Divider with some flush cutters.


Run out of Abandoned Space Probes

Obviously, just print some more! The number of Abandoned Space Probes needed stated in the Game Instructions (link above) is a calculated average. So it can vary upon the player's guessing ability. Maybe smaller kids will need much more... ¯\_(ツ)_/¯


Have fun and please share your thoughts and prints!

Peace ;)

title: Foolscap To A4 Suspension FIle Adaptor

description.text:
Just a simple adaptor piece that allows you to use standard A4 size filing wallets onside of a filing cabinet meant for the larger Foolscap sized ones instead.

I had loads of the A4 sized ones around, and sadly only had a Foolscap filing cabinet, so made the adaptor to save me buying new wallets.

The one included is 12cm long, I had to print a couple of these to fit the length of my drawers, but obviously your draws will be different lengths so I have included both the STL and the SKP file so you can tinker as you wish.

The Adaptor Stopper part has a wider lip at the back. This is designed for the rear of your drawers to stop your files from falling of the track at the rear.

Seperating

As the parts are quite thin and tall, its recommended to print them side by side (as I have laid them out) so they use each other for support.

Because of this, the gap between the two parts is set at 0.4mm (my nozzle width). The parts will separate from the bed as one piece however because the plastic is lightly fused due to the small gap.

They will separate very easily if you just slide something in between the two parts such as a screwdriver and just lever a little, do this on each end and they will easily come apart with no marks on the parts.

title: Kongo's Jolly Jelly Christmas Lights
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Celebrate the nativity with an undersea twist.
Perhaps the theme of your prom is "Under the Sea."
Or maybe your cubicle could use something that suggests tranquility.

Whatever the use, I'm sure everything will seem more jolly when these jellies swim into your life.

Printer:

Ordbot Hadron

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.25

Infill:

100%

Notes:

This model was designed with clear PETG in mind. PLA is not recommended. I've printed two jellies in PLA, both broke at the "oral arms" (the leafy things). I've printed a few dozen PETG jellies, none have broken.

The model has a built in brim, so leave that feature off in your slicer.

1. Remove the brim

The brim can be peeled off by hand, but PETG layers can fuse together strongly, and I found it easier to use an x-acto knife.

2. Adding the tentacles (the wavy stringy-things)

The holes for the tentacles are sized for 1.75 filament, but I decided to use 50lb monofilament fishing line (its thickness is more to jellyfish scale). Put some superglue in the holes, and push the end of a 75mm long pieces of filament in each hole.

Though the fishing line looked good curved (its shape as it comes off the roll), I decided I wanted to give it more character. I built a jig using nails and scrap wood. The nails are hammered 1/2" apart, and the filament is woven between them, as seen in the photo below (The photo keeps disappearing for some reason -- if it's gone again, look for it in the project gallery up top). To get the line to hold the wavy shape, cook the line in a low temp oven (I didn't test temperatures or times, but 250°F/120°C for ~5-10 minutes worked for me). Let the monofilament cool before removing it.

3. Attach to lights

Use the jellies only with lights that don't get too warm. I've left enough ventilation for LED strings, and probably for most of the old mini incandescent strings, but YOU ARE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SAFETY OF YOUR LOVED ONES!

ENJOY!

I hope you have a jolly time with the jellies! If you like them, please consider tipping -- I appreciate any amount!

The jellies were made entirely in Blender. They aren't modeled on a particular species, I just chose features that would allow light transmission, and avoided those that would block it.

You wouldn't know by looking at them, but this project had a long gestation period. My earliest files for them are over three years old! I bought the filament for them over a year ago. Were they that complicated to make?

No, it's just that my Christmases have been filled with various crises that last few years. I was beginning to think there was a jelly curse on me. So far, this year has been fine -- knocks on wood.

Hey, people who sell prints on sites like Etsy:

Please note this design is released under the CC-BY-NC-SA license. That doesn't mean you can't sell them, it just means you need to contact me about being granted a commercial license. We can negotiate a tip arrangement, and I'll link to your store here, if you wish.
